x\sqrt3 = x + \sqrt3.
 \begin{array}{rcl}   x\sqrt{3}  &=& x + \sqrt{3}\\   x\sqrt{3} - x &=& \sqrt{3}\\   x(\sqrt{3} - 1) &=& \sqrt{3} \\   x &=& \frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{3} - 1}\\   \textrm{Now rationalize the denominator:}&&\\   x &=& \frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{3} - 1}\cdot \frac{\sqrt{3} + 1}{\sqrt{3} + 1}\\   x &=& \frac{3+\sqrt{3}}{3 - 1}\\   x &=& \frac{3+\sqrt{3}}{2}\\   \textrm{Finally, write in the required form:}&&\\   x &=& \frac{1}{2} \sqrt{3} + \frac{3}{2}.   \end{array} 
\sqrt 3x=x+\sqrt 3\implies (\sqrt 3-1)x=\sqrt 3\implies x=\frac{\sqrt 3}{\sqrt 3-1}=\frac{\sqrt 3(\sqrt 3+1)}{(\sqrt 3-1)(\sqrt 3+1)}=\frac{3+\sqrt3}2
\sqrt ax=bx+\sqrt c\implies x=\frac{\sqrt c}{\sqrt a-b}=\frac{\sqrt c(\sqrt a+b)}{(\sqrt a-b)(\sqrt a+b)}=\frac{\sqrt{ac}+\sqrt cb}{a-b^2}
a=c,
\sqrt ax=bx+\sqrt a\implies x=\frac{a+\sqrt ab}{a-b^2}
a=3,b=1
